msgid "*Slide 4 - Definitions - a rose by any other name*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:69
msgid ""
"Let’s focus for a moment on some common words and phrases that contain the "
"word data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide5.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 5 - What's the difference - Database*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:75
msgid ""
"All of the phrases here include the word data, but are they all the same, "
"and if not, then what is the difference?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:76
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide6.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 6 - Database*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:81
msgid "So, what is a “Database”?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:83
msgid ""
"There are many definitions, but what they all have in common is the theme "
"that a database is a structured and organized collection of data and/or "
"information held on a computer."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:84
msgid ""
"Everything else in the list is just a way to help you achieve this data "
"nirvana!"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:85
msgid "Let’s dig a little deeper then into those other terms."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:86
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide7.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 7 - Database language*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:91
msgid "Let us take a look at the phrase “database language”."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:93
msgid ""
"According to the Oxford English dictionary “language” is the method of human "
"communication...consisting of the use of words (or symbols) in a structured "
"and conventional way."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:95
msgid ""
"For our purposes, database languages and their close allies the array "
"languages are the way by which a human communicates with a computer to "
"manipulate and move around data."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:97
msgid "Examples that you may have come across are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:99
msgid "Java, SPARQL, SQL and Python"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:100
msgid ""
"They are simply methods used to define and create tables, views and queries "
"and also allow users to access, update, store and move data around."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:101
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide8.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:104
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 8 - Database program/software*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:106
msgid "Now let’s look at the phrase “database program or software”."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:108
msgid ""
"Again going to the Oxford English dictionary a “program/programme” is a set "
"of related measures or activities with a particular long-term aim."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:110
msgid ""
"In this context, a “database program or software” combines and presents "
"functions and features for manipulating data, together is a unified "
"interface."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:112
msgid "Examples that you may come across are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:114
msgid "Microsoft Access, FilemakerPro and Oracle"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:116
msgid ""
"So, database programs or software are grouped utilities which allow a user, "
"via a database language, to store, manage, query and report data held in the "
"system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:117
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide9.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:120
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 9 - Data cleaning tool*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:122
msgid "The last term is “data cleaning tool”."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:124
msgid ""
"Data cleaning tools are systems whose utilities focus is on the manipulation "
"of data with the aim of increasing fitness for use."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:126
msgid ""
"Examples that you may be familiar or will learn about during the course are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:128
msgid "OpenRefine, MatLab and spreadsheets"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:130
msgid ""
"A data cleaning tool should assist the user in the discovery and repair of "
"messy data in order to increase quality."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:131
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide10.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:134
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 10 - Definitions - a rose by any other name*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:136
msgid ""
"Continuing on with some more terms that you should be familiar with we will "
"look at the differences between the terms Field, Label and List."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:137
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide11.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:140
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 11 - Field vs label*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:142
msgid ""
"You will often hear reference made to field or column names and field labels "
"or headings. Often they will be used interchangeably, however they are "
"different things."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:144
msgid ""
"Field or column names refer to the actual column in the database table. They "
"are a often short, not always in plain language, sometimes computer "
"generated; but in a properly formed database they are ALWAYS unique. Field "
"names are almost always used by database languages, because the avoid "
"ambiguity."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:146
msgid ""
"Labels and headers on the other hand, refer to the human readable versions "
"of the field names. Most often you will see these in the graphical user "
"interface of your software and on exports and reports. In some software you "
"can in fact have different labels to the same field on a user by user or "
"group basis!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:147
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide12.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:150
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 12 - Lists*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:152
msgid ""
"As you work with your data you will come across the phrases “drop-down list” "
"and “controlled vocabulary” and on the surface they can appear to be the "
"same. Indeed they are both powerful tools to help you keep your data clean, "
"but they are different."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:154
msgid ""
"A drop-down list, also sometimes called a lookup table is a data entry "
"element that is created in your database software. It allows to you select a "
"value from a predefined set of options. They can also be generated from the "
"data itself on the fly."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:156
msgid ""
"A controlled vocabulary on the other hand, is a very strictly defined, "
"domain specific set of values that should be applied to a particular field. "
"They are an integral part of a well defined standard. Such values can be "
"used in a drop-down list as mentioned previously."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:157
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide13.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:160
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 13 - Definitions - a rose by any other name*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:162
msgid ""
"In this section we will look at what the term character means in relation to "
"data and computers."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:163
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide14.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:166
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 14 - Characters*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:168
msgid ""
"As a reminder computers “see” in binary. Everything that you type in, is "
"held in memory as a series of ones and zeros."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:171
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The computer does not “see” the repertoire of letters and symbols on your keyboard.\n"
"\vIt needs a map to translate the character set that you would write or type, into its binary language and then back again to show it to you on the screen or a printer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:173
msgid "This map is made up of two parts:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:175
msgid "The “coded character set”"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:177
msgid "and"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:179
msgid "The “character encoding”"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:181
msgid ""
"Each symbol or glyph is assigned a numeric value and that number is then "
"converted to binary."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:182
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide15.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:185
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 15 - Characters example*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:187
msgid ""
"In this example we see how character encoding is used to map the capital "
"letter A in the western alphabet."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:189
msgid "The ASCII value for the capital letter A is the decimal number 65"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:191
msgid "which in HEXIDECIMAL is 041"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:193
msgid "and in BINARY 01000001"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:195
msgid ""
"Try mapping your own name to Binary using the link at the bottom of the "
"screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:196
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide16.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 16 - Characters comparison*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:201
msgid ""
"In effect what is happening is that when you type into a keyboard and save a "
"file the software that you are using will select an encoding to save with it."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:203
msgid ""
"When you open that file again the software needs to know which encoding "
"(map) to use to redisplay the information back to you correctly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:204
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide17.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:207
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 17 - Characters*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:209
msgid "So why is this important to you as a data custodian?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:211
msgid "Let’s say that you translate the start of Hamlet’s soliloquy"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:213
msgid " ”To be or not to be, that is the question”"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:215
msgid ""
"into French and then save the file with a text editor that uses the encoding "
"Latin-1"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:217
msgid "Then you send it to a colleague to check the translation. Voila!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:218
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide18.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:221
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 18 - Characters*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:223
msgid "When they open the file in MicroSoft Word this is what they see."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:225
msgid "Mon dieu!"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:227
msgid "There are some unexpected characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:229
msgid ""
"You forgot to tell your colleague that you where using Latin-1 as the "
"encoding."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:231
msgid ""
"MicroSoft Word on their end was set to use the encoding set Unicode UTF-8. "
"The maps did not match."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:233
msgid "Depending on the software the data may be irretrievably corrupted."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:234
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide19.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:237
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 19 - Review*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:239
msgid "In review we have looked at the differences between the phrases:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:241
msgid "Database; database language; database program, data-cleaning tool"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:242
msgid ""
"Field names & Field labels; Drop-down lists & Controlled vocabularies and "
"between"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:243
msgid "Repertoires, Coded sets & Encodings"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:245
msgid ""
"And shown that although the terms may seem similar the in fact have very "
"different definitions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:246
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide20.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:249
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 20 - Wrap-up*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:252
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:396
msgid "Remember that:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:254
msgid ""
"“...The first step in wisdom is to know the things themselves; this notion "
"consists in having a true idea of the objects.”"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:256
msgid ""
"We often take for granted that there is a whole language associated with "
"biodiversity informatics that is not commonplace and has to be learned. "
"There is no shame in going back to basics and getting to grips with the "
"vocabulary, grammar and syntax just like with any new language."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:257
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-terminology-Slide21.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:260
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 21 - Conclusion*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:262
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:406
msgid ""
"This video is part of a series of presentations used in the GBIF "
"Biodiversity Data Mobilization course. The biodiversity data mobilization "
"curriculum was originally developed as part of the Biodiversity Information "
"Development Programme funded by the European Union."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:264
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:716
msgid ""
"This presentation was originally created and narrated by Sharon Grant with "
"additional contributions by BID and BIFA Trainers, Mentors and Students."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:268
#, no-wrap
msgid "Software"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:273
msgid ""
"In this video (05:58), you will review examples of the different types of "
"applications and software available in the world of biodiversity "
"mobilization informatics."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:275
msgid ""
"If you are unable to watch the embedded video, you can xref:"
"attachment$foundations-software_v1-720p.mp4[download,opts=download] it "
"locally. (MP4 - 23.5 MB)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:292
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide1.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:295
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 1 - Foundations - Software terminology*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:297
msgid ""
"This session is foundation work and part of the Terminology section We will "
"be introducing you to types of software used in data mobilization."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:300
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide2.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:303
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 2 - Software for mobilization*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:305
msgid ""
"The purpose of this short presentation is to give you some examples of the "
"different types of applications and software available in the world of "
"biodiversity mobilization informatics."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:307
msgid ""
"Hopefully it will help you to start to think about what uses they may be put "
"too and what types of things might be practical for you."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:308
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide3.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:311
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 3 - Software definition*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:313
msgid "So very briefly, a definition."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:315
msgid ""
"We are making a distinction here between all software and those applications "
"which have been created for an end-user to carry out a task."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:317
msgid "We will take a look at software that can be used for:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:319
msgid "Data Capture"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:320
msgid "Data Management"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:321
msgid "Data Cleaning and"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:322
msgid "Data Publishing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:323
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide4.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:326
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 4 - Software for data capture*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:328
msgid ""
"In the realm of data capture software, there is often no need to go “big” "
"when capturing information initially, especially in the field."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:330
msgid ""
"You can capture information from collection specimens or live observations "
"in a simple spreadsheet such as:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:332
msgid "Excel, OpenOffice, LibreOffice or Google Sheets."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:334
msgid ""
"There may even not be a need to create your own system at all. Apps such as "
"iNaturalist, or eBird are stable, robust and have simple intuitive "
"interfaces."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:336
msgid ""
"Whichever the choice, it is important to think about the long term "
"preservation of the data that you collect."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:337
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide5.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:340
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 5 - Software for data management*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:342
msgid ""
"So, depending on your needs, a more complex data management software might "
"be the right solution for your data. Especially if long term retention and "
"preservation is a priority."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:344
msgid ""
"More stable management platforms also better support sharing of data to "
"multiple audiences."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:346
msgid ""
"There are many choices which vary in terms of cost and support and a few are "
"shown here. From left to right:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:348
msgid "Symbiota, Specify, EMu, Elysia and Brahms."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:349
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide6.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:352
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 6 - Software for data capture and management*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:354
msgid ""
"If a home-grown solution is preferred and can be supported, relational "
"database software can provide cheaper alternatives."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:356
msgid "Examples incluse MySQL, SQLServer, Access or filemaker"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:357
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide7.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:360
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 7 - Software for data cleaning*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:362
msgid ""
"Increasingly the lines between languages, programs and tools have blurred, "
"each being capable of many complex and overlapping functions. The common "
"“Find and Replace” function is a good example of a data cleaning tool that "
"is found in almost all database programs and is a command in database "
"languages."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:364
msgid ""
"You are probably already familiar with spreadsheets such as Excel and indeed "
"these are probably the most common data cleaning tools available. However "
"there are others."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:366
msgid ""
"OpenRefine originally known as GoogleRefine is a powerful free, open source "
"data cleaning tool with a large support community. You will see more of this "
"program in upcoming sessions."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:368
msgid ""
"R is another increasing used, sophisticated programming language and "
"environment. With a little practice it can also provide powerful data "
"manipulations."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:369
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide8.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:372
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 8 - Software for data publishing*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:374
msgid ""
"Planning further ahead to the sharing of your data through GBIF to the "
"international scientific and deciders community you will need to choose a "
"publishing tool."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:376
msgid ""
"The choice will depend largely on the level of infrastructure support at "
"your institution. If this is high and stable, installing an IPT or BioCASe "
"application may be the right option. But there are others if this is not the "
"case."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:378
msgid ""
"You can consider partnering with an existing ipt provider or selecting a "
"database management system that includes a publishing pathway of its own."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:380
msgid ""
"Whichever you choose, make sure that your system allows you to export data "
"as csv or txt files and you will ultimately be able to publish your data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:381
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide9.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:384
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 9 - Other software to handle data*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:386
msgid ""
"This is a summary of the information collected in the course survey of "
"software in use by students, mentors and trainers in the GBIF community."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:388
msgid ""
"The link and reference to more details of each section, is at the bottom of "
"the slide."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:390
msgid ""
"Reference: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1IWBsL4r-"
"LsJRdYYPy9q4eLOAa1nzZYBwTdwk3Kd8cV8/"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:391
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide10.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:394
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 10 - Wrap-up*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:398
msgid ""
"“The purpose of software is to help people” and not the other way around."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:400
msgid ""
"Your choice of solution should make your life easier but it should also not "
"sacrifice the long term viability of the data that it is meant to work with."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:401
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-software-Slide11.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:404
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 11 - Conclusion*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:408
msgid ""
"This presentation was narrated by Sharon Grant with additional contributions "
"by BID and BIFA Trainers, Mentors and Students."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:412
#, no-wrap
msgid "Structures"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:417
msgid ""
"In this video (13:10), you will review the field and data types that hold "
"data, the structures that help to organize and protect that data and what "
"these mean for the integrity and security of your data."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:419
msgid ""
"If you are unable to watch the embedded video, you can xref:"
"attachment$foundations-structures_v1-720p.mp4[download,opts=download] it "
"locally.  (MP4 - 44.4 MB)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:436
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide1.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:439
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 1 - Foundations - Structures terminology*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:444
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide2.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:451
msgid ""
"In the section on STRUCTURES we will be working on understanding the field "
"and data types that hold data, the structures that help to organize and "
"protect that data and lastly look at what these mean for the integrity and "
"security of your data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:452
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide3.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:455
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 3 - Structures*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:457
msgid ""
"In this section on basic database Structures we will focus on the different "
"elements that databases, software tools and languages use to handle the data "
"that you enter."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:458
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide4.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:461
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 4 - Structures - Planes, trains and automobiles*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:463
msgid "First, lets look at field types, also known as data types."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:464
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide5.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:467
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 5 - Containers – field/data types*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:469
msgid ""
"Data Type lets the computer know what kind of data is expected in a "
"particular field. This then dictates what functions can be performed on it."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:471
msgid ""
"They can be simple and encompass a single concept or combine concepts "
"depending on the software or language you are using. Either way the "
"essential building blocks are the same."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:473
msgid "So let’s look at six that you will come across most frequently."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:474
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide6.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:477
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 6 - Containers – field/data types*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:479
msgid ""
"First Numeric fields – This data type holds numbers, and there are 2 kinds: "
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:481
msgid ""
"Integers and long integers, hold whole numbers. For example 1, 2, 3, 99, "
"2000."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:483
msgid ""
"The size of the number, depends on the number of bits assigned to the field "
"(more about that later). For now just remember that a long integer field "
"will hold a bigger number than an integer."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:485
msgid ""
"Floats, also referred to as doubles, hold fractions or parts of whole "
"numbers. For example 4.5, 19.47"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:487
msgid ""
"The important thing to remember here is that a float always has decimal "
"places so the number 10 will be stored as 10.0. The number of decimal places "
"being an integral element of the type. This has implications when it comes "
"to precision and accuracy."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:488
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide7.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:491
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 7 - Containers – field/data types*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:493
msgid ""
"Alphanumeric fields - are also referred to as text, character or string "
"fields."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:495
msgid ""
"They can hold any letter, number or symbol in the coded character set and "
"usually have a defined character limit. Entering more characters than the "
"character limit can often result in truncation and loss of data on save."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:496
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide8.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:499
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 8 - Containers – field/data types*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:501
msgid ""
"Another type of text field that you will come across is the Unstructured "
"text field, also known as memo, long char or blob fields."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:503
msgid ""
"These types of field are used to hold large amounts of unformatted text and "
"unlike alphanumeric fields may not have an obvious character limit."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:505
msgid ""
"In simple systems, they are generally less flexible in terms of processing; "
"for example sorting and indexing, than their smaller alphanumeric cousins."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:507
msgid ""
"With decreased storage costs and the rise of NoSQL document-oriented "
"database programs, such as MongoDB however, this is changing."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:508
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide9.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:511
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 9 - Containers – field/data types*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:513
msgid ""
"System Value fields have a double nature and what you see on the screen is "
"not usually the actual value that the software is storing in memory. Date "
"and time fields are the most common example of this type of field."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:515
msgid ""
"In this example you typed “1 March 1971” into a cell in Excel and hit return."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:517
msgid "Now it says “1-Mar-71” in the cell AND “3/1/1971” in the functionbar."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:519
msgid ""
"Excel is applying a display format to the cell, which you can change at will."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:521
msgid ""
"HOWEVER, if you remove the format you see that what is actually being stored "
"in the field is the number 25993.00!"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:523
msgid ""
"So you can see that the field is actually a float. You should beware because "
"that system value not be the same from software to software. Exports should "
"to checked to make sure the actual date is exported and not the system value."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:524
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide10.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:527
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 10 - Containers – field/data types*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:529
msgid ""
"Boolean fields – also known as Binary fields only contain one of two values "
"that represent a one or a zero."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:531
msgid ""
"They are a special case of a System Value field as mentioned previously in "
"that whilst the software actually saves a number it often displays values "
"such as:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:536
msgid "Yes/No; Yes/no; Y/N; True/False. "
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:538
msgid ""
"You should take care to find out which way around the system you are using "
"translates."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:540
msgid "Is a 1 a yes or no?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:541
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide11.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:544
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 11 - Containers – field/data types*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:546
msgid ""
"Structured Text fields are less common but mentioned here for completeness."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:548
msgid ""
"They are fields which can be either made up of combinations of the simple "
"data types or even be defined by the data itself."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:550
msgid ""
"Most often these are used in programming languages to allow flexibility and "
"handling of complex concepts."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:552
msgid ""
"An example is the factor field used in the R programming language, which is "
"defined as a type vector containing a set of numeric codes with character-"
"valued levels."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:554
msgid ""
"Ref:  https://www.stat.berkeley.edu/~nolan/stat133/Fall05/lectures/"
"DataTypes4.pdf"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:555
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide12.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:558
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 12 - Structures - planes, trains and automobiles*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:560
msgid ""
"Now that you have an understanding of the field types used to represent your "
"data elements let’s talk about the containers or structures, that many "
"database programs and software use collate and display your data."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:562
msgid "Reference: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/data-structures/"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:563
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide13.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:566
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 13 - Containers - Data structures*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:568
msgid "First is the cell."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:570
msgid ""
"This is the smallest data structure, it holds a single value and has a "
"single data type associated with it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:571
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide14.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:574
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 14 - Data structures*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:578
msgid ""
"There is one concept that you should beware of when it comes to cells and "
"that is the “empty cell”.    “An empty cell doesn’t necessarily mean an "
"empty field.”"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:580
msgid ""
"Some software “fills” an empty field with a System value based on the data "
"type."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:582
msgid "Examples are “NULL” “N A” or even zero!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:583
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide15.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:586
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 15 - Containers - Data structures*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:588
msgid ""
"As you start to organize cells you begin to build a grid. Grids have implied "
"structure in the form of"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:590
msgid "Rows"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:591
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide16.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:594
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 16 - Containers - Data structures*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:596
msgid "And columns."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:597
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide17.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:600
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 17 - Containers - Data structures*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:602
msgid ""
"When you organize cells into rows and columns, obviously, what you get is a "
"grid!"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:604
msgid "This is looks very much like a spreadsheet right?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:606
msgid ""
"Well, yes. The difference however between a spreadsheet grid and a table are "
"the strength of the ties that hold the rows and columns together."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:607
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide18.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:610
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 18 - Structures - planes, trains and automobiles*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:612
msgid "So let’s now talk about those connections."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:614
msgid ""
"What the implications for the integrity and security of your data of loose "
"unenforced relationships between rows and columns?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:615
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide19.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:618
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 19 - Data structures*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:620
msgid ""
"What actually makes a table useful are the connections that we create to "
"give the data in the structure meaning."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:622
msgid ""
"We intrinsically make patterns of attributes that turns data into "
"information."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:624
msgid "Rows become records and Columns become attributes"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:626
msgid ""
"In a spreadsheet however, the connections between cells are idiomatic, loose "
"and un-enforced."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:628
msgid ""
"It is easy for the attributes between the rows to get jumbled up or for the "
"values get changed and then the meaning is lost."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:629
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide20.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:632
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 20 - Integrity and security*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:634
msgid ""
"This lack of enforced connections makes a spreadsheet easy to use but these "
"same qualities also cause problems."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:636
msgid "Errors are easy to make and hard to catch."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:638
msgid ""
"Connections and relationships are not documentable and so subject to "
"interpretation and mutation."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:640
msgid ""
"Spreadsheets are not built to scale either in terms of size or numbers of "
"users."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:642
msgid "So can be slow, crashy and easily corruptible"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:644
msgid "Spreadsheets are easy to copy and email"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:646
msgid "So they are hard to version and keep track of"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:648
msgid "The question is what is the solution?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:650
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:688
msgid ""
"Reference: https://www.mrc-productivity.com/blog/2014/09/7-dangers-of-"
"spreadsheets-part-1/"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:651
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide21.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:654
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 21 - Containers - Integrity and security*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:656
msgid "Let’s look back, at the connections in a bit more detail."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:658
msgid ""
"We generally understand that the data in each row of a table means something."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:660
msgid ""
"For example each row can represent a specimen or a taxa that was found at a "
"particular place, at a particular time, by a particular person."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:662
msgid ""
"It would be odd to have one row in a table that represents a specimen "
"followed by a row that represents a collection site."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:664
msgid ""
"We also often want to analyse, sort and compare values of particular "
"attributes between rows."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:666
msgid "For example you may want find the mean weight of all the Kenyan bats."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:668
msgid "So ideally we want to use a system to store our data that:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:670
msgid "always holds the rows together"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:671
msgid "does not mix data types"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:672
msgid "and segregates data in each table to a single concept or theme"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:674
msgid "These are functions of a database!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:675
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide22.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:680
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Slide 22 - Integrity and security*\n"
" \n"
"Functions in a true database inherently bind rows together and columns may only have a single data type.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:682
msgid "Tables in database are held together by virtual links called keys."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:684
msgid ""
"These keys are identifiers that match between tables and allow data to be "
"connected efficiently."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:686
msgid ""
"It is these 2 key concepts that distinguish a spreadsheet from a database."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:689
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide23.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:694
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Slide 23 - Review*\n"
" \n"
"In review then, we have looked at the 6 most common data types, the basic building blocks of data structure and distinguished between a spreadsheet grid and database table.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:696
msgid ""
"Understanding these elements and how they interact with one another will "
"allow you to better determine the best ways to manipulate and document the "
"data that falls under your custodianship."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:697
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide24.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:702
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Slide 24 - Wrap-up*\n"
" \n"
"Remember that: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:704
msgid ""
"“When you realize the difference between the container and the content, you "
"will have knowledge.”"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:706
msgid ""
"Using the correct terms to describe both your data and the structures that "
"you create and use to store it; is the most important way to ensure that it "
"remains relevant and useable."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:708
msgid ""
"Never underestimate how much damage can be done to priceless information by "
"careless descriptions and storage."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:709
#, no-wrap
msgid "foundations::foundations-structures-Slide25.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/foundations/modules/ROOT/pages/foundations-terminology.adoc:714
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Slide 25 - Conclusion*\n"
" \n"
